I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the API data, as this is the first step in the workflow. I'll use the default URL "https://api.example.com/data" as specified in the test environment rules.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll use the data_processing_validator tool to validate the fetched data. Since we don't have a specific schema, I'll use a generic validation schema that checks for basic JSON structure.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "object"
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": {"data": {}},
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

The validation failed, likely because we didn't have the actual fetched data to validate. I'll first retrieve the data from the network_fetcher output using the data_processing_parser tool before attempting validation again.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now that we have successfully parsed the data, I'll attempt the validation again using the data_processing_validator tool with the parsed data. I'll use a basic schema that checks for common API response structure.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "status": {"type": "string"},
      "data": {"type": "object"},
      "timestamp": {"type": "string"}
    },
    "required": ["status", "data"]
  },
  "data": {
    "status": "completed",
    "data": {},
    "timestamp": "2025-08-28T01:12:12.788744"
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll use the data_processing_transformer tool to prepare the data for posting. I'll transform the validated data into a simplified format for the API post request.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "json",
  "options": {
    "transformations": [
      {
        "operation": "extract",
        "fields": ["data"],
        "target": "payload"
      },
      {
        "operation": "add",
        "field": "metadata.timestamp",
        "value": "2025-08-28T01:12:14.788368"
      }
    ]
  }
}
</tool_call>

            I'll use the network_poster tool to send the transformed data to the API endpoint. I'll use the default destination URL and the transformed data from the previous step.

<tool_call>network_poster
{
  "destination": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "data": {
    "payload": {},
    "metadata": {
      "timestamp": "2025-08-28T01:12:18.955255"
    }
  },
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>
